window.__QUIZ_DATA__=[{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2021>1>a","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2021","type":"Practical","sub_label":"a","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"SIMPLE HARMONIC MOTION : PERIOD, FREQUENCY AND AMPLITUDE OF A BODY EXECUTING S.H.M","question":"You are provided with a set of masses, two metre rules, a piece of thread, two retort stands and clamps, a stop watch, split corks and a weighing balance.  Use the diagram above as a guide to perform the experiment.   (i) Measure and record the mass, M, of the metre rule.   (ii) Suspend the metre rule, whose mass has been measured, by means of two vertical strings of equal lengths,  l  = 70 cm.   (iii) Make the separation between the threads, d = 80 cm.   (iv) Suspend a mass m = 20 g from the mid-point of the metre rule by means of a thread such that the distance between the mass and the rule, h = 15 cm.  (v) Displace the ends of the metre rule in a horizontal plane in opposite directions. Release the rule to perform horizontal oscillations.  (vi) Determine the time, t for 20 oscillations.  (vii) Evaluate the period T, T2 and T-2.  (viii) Repeat the procedure for four other values of m = 30 g, 50 g, 70g and 100 g keeping the values of h, d and  l  constant. In each case, determine t and evaluate T, T2 and T-2.  (ix) Tabulate the results.  (x) Plot a graph with T-2 on the vertical axis and m on the horizontal axis.  (xi) Determine the slope, s, of the graph.  (xii) State two precautions taken to ensure accurate results.","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,","data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"M = 132.6 g    S/Nm(g)t1(s)t2(s)t = t1+t22\\frac{t_{1}+t_{2}}{2}2t1\u200b+t2\u200b\u200b(s)T = tn\\frac{t}{n}nt\u200b(s)T2(s2)T-2(s-2)12023.3723.3823.381.1691.3670.731823022.7822.8122.801.1401.3000.769535021.0621.4721.241.0621.1280.886647020.5320.3220.431.0221.0440.9574510019.0019.0019.000.9500.9031.1080        (xi) s = \u25b3T\u22122\u25b3m\\frac{\u25b3T^{-2}}{\u25b3m}\u25b3m\u25b3T\u22122\u200b = T2\u22122\u2212T1\u22122m2\u2212m1\\frac{T^{-2}_{2}-T^{-2}_{1}}{m_{2}-m_{1}}m2\u200b\u2212m1\u200bT2\u22122\u200b\u2212T1\u22122\u200b\u200b = 1.108\u22120.7318100\u221220\\frac{1.108-0.7318}{100-20}100\u2212201.108\u22120.7318\u200b = 0.376280\\frac{0.3762}{80}800.3762\u200b = 4.7 \u00d7 10-3 s-2g-1    (x) Precautions:    1. I ensured that the strings suspending the metre rule were of equal lengths to maintain balance and uniform oscillation.    2. I avoided parallax errors when reading the metre rule, stopwatch to ensure precise measurements.    3. I checked and corrected for any zero error on the stopwatch before taking readings.    4. I ensured the retort stands and clamps were stable and rigid to prevent unwanted movement during the experiment.    5. I used small displacements when initiating the oscillations to approximate simple harmonic motion.    6. I avoided draughts or any external disturbances that could affect the uniformity of the oscillations.    7. I confirmed that the mass was securely attached at the midpoint of the metre rule to maintain consistent conditions across trials.    8. I repeated the experiment multiple times for each mass and recorded all data systematically to identify and minimize any random errors.    9. I ensured the oscillations were purely horizontal and avoided any conical motion that could affect timing accuracy.","marks":"21","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2021>1>b>i","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2021","type":"Practical","sub_label":"i","group":"","topic":"SIMPLE HARMONIC MOTION : PERIOD, FREQUENCY AND AMPLITUDE OF A BODY EXECUTING S.H.M","question":"Define the period of an oscillatory motion.","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"The period of an oscillatory motion is the time taken to complete one full cycle of motion. It is denoted by T and is typically measured in seconds (s). For a system undergoing periodic motion, such as a pendulum or a spring, the period depends on factors such as the system's physical properties and the restoring force acting on it. Mathematically, the period is related to the frequency (f) by the equation:    T = 1f\\frac{1}{f}f1\u200b    where f is the number of cycles per second (in hertz).","marks":"2","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2021>1>b>ii","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2021","type":"Practical","sub_label":"ii","group":"","topic":"GRAVITATIONAL FIELD : ACCELERATION DUE TO GRAVITY","question":"State two differences between mass and weight.","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"Here are several differences between mass and weight:    1. Definition:    Mass is the measure of the amount of matter in an object.  Weight is the force exerted by gravity on an object.    2. Nature:    Mass is a scalar quantity (it has magnitude only).  Weight is a vector quantity (it has both magnitude and direction).    3. Dependence:    Mass is constant and does not change with location.  Weight varies depending on the gravitational field strength (e.g., it is different on the Earth, Moon, or Mars).    4. Unit of Measurement:    Mass is measured in kilograms (kg) or grams (g).  Weight is measured in newtons (N), as it is a force.    5. Instrument of Measurement:    Mass is measured using a balance (e.g., a beam balance or electronic balance).  Weight is measured using a spring balance or force meter.    6. Formula:    Mass is a fundamental property and does not depend on gravity.  Weight is calculated using W = mg, where m is mass and g is gravitational acceleration.    7. Effect in Space:    An object retains its mass even in zero gravity.  An object's weight becomes zero in the absence of gravity.    These differences illustrate the distinct physical concepts of mass and weight.","marks":"2","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2021>2>a","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2021","type":"Practical","sub_label":"a","group":"","topic":"LIGHT WAVES : REFRACTION OF LIGHT AT CURVED SURFACES","question":"You are provided with an illuminated object, a lens, a screen, a lens holder and a metre rule.  Use the diagram above as a guide to perform the experiment.  (i) Determine the approximate focal length, fo the lens by focusing a distant object on the screen.  (ii) Place the illuminated object and the screen a distance D = 100 cm apart.  (iii) Place the lens at a position S1, to obtain a sharp image of the object on the screen. Note S1.  (iv) Move the lens to a position S2 to obtain another sharp image of the object on the screen. Note S2.  (v) Measure the distance, d, between S1, and S2  (vi) Evaluate D-1, D2, d2 and d2D2\\frac{d^{2}}{D^{2}}D2d2\u200b.  (vii) Repeat the procedure for four other values of D = 90 cm, 85 cm, 80 cm and 70 cm. In each case, evaluate D-1, D2, d2 and d2D2\\frac{d^{2}}{D^{2}}D2d2\u200b.  (viii) Tabulate the results.  (x) Plot a graph with d2D2\\frac{d^{2}}{D^{2}}D2d2\u200b on the vertical axis and D-1 on the horizontal axis.  (x) Determine the slope, s, of the graph.  (xi) Given that s = 4k, determine k.  (xii) State two precautions taken to ensure accurate results.","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,","data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"fo = 16 cm    S/ND(cm)d(cm)D2(cm2)d2(cm2)d2D2\\frac{d^{2}}{D^{2}}D2d2\u200bD-1(cm-1)1100.063.01000039690.39690.010290.051.0810026010.32110.011385.045.0722520250.28030.012480.038.0640014440.22560.013570.025.049006250.12760.014        (x) s = \u25b3d2D2\u25b3D\u22121\\frac{\u25b3\\frac{d^{2}}{D^{2}}}{\u25b3D^{-1}}\u25b3D\u22121\u25b3D2d2\u200b\u200b = (d2D2)2\u2212(d2D2)1D2\u22121\u2212D1\u22121\\frac{\\left(\\frac{d^{2}}{D^{2}}\\right)_{2}-\\left(\\frac{d^{2}}{D^{2}}\\right)_{1}}{D^{-1}_{2}-D^{-1}_{1}}D2\u22121\u200b\u2212D1\u22121\u200b(D2d2\u200b)2\u200b\u2212(D2d2\u200b)1\u200b\u200b = 0.4\u22120.140.01\u22120.014\\frac{0.4-0.14}{0.01-0.014}0.01\u22120.0140.4\u22120.14\u200b = 0.26\u22120.004\\frac{0.26}{-0.004}\u22120.0040.26\u200b = -65 cm    (xi) s = 4k    k = s4\\frac{s}{4}4s\u200b = \u2212654\\frac{-65}{4}4\u221265\u200b = 16.25 cm    (xii) **Precautions:    1. I ensured that the lens was thoroughly cleaned to eliminate smudges and dirt, which could affect the clarity and accuracy of observations.    2. I carefully avoided parallax errors by positioning my eyes perpendicularly to the scale markings while reading the metre rule.    3. I verified the lens was properly aligned in a stable and upright position during the experiment to maintain accuracy.    4. I took repeated readings to enhance precision and reduce the effects of random errors.    5. I ensured the experimental setup was free from external vibrations or disturbances, which could affect results.","marks":"21","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2021>2>b>i","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2021","type":"Practical","sub_label":"i","group":"","topic":"LIGHT WAVES : REFRACTION OF LIGHT AT CURVED SURFACES","question":"Draw and label the ray diagram of a simple microscope","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,","data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"","marks":"2","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2021>2>b>ii","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2021","type":"Practical","sub_label":"ii","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"LIGHT WAVES : REFRACTION OF LIGHT AT CURVED SURFACES","question":"State two differences between a real image and virtual image","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"Here are several differences between a real image and a virtual image:    1. Formation:    A real image is formed when light rays converge after reflection or refraction.  A virtual image is formed when light rays diverge but appear to converge when extended backward.    2. Position:    Real images are always formed on the same side as the screen or opposite to the object.  Virtual images are always formed on the same side as the object.    3. Projection:    A real image can be projected onto a screen.  A virtual image cannot be projected onto a screen.    4. Orientation:    Real images are inverted relative to the object.  Virtual images are upright (erect) relative to the object.    5. Examples:    Real images: Image formed on a cinema screen or by a camera lens.  Virtual images: Image seen in a plane mirror or through a magnifying glass.    6. Ray Diagram:    For real images, the light rays physically intersect.  For virtual images, the light rays only appear to intersect when traced backward.","marks":"2","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2021>3>a","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2021","type":"Practical","sub_label":"a","group":"","topic":"ELECTRIC FIELD : ELECTRIC CURRENT, POTENTIAL DIFFERENCE, RESISTANCE, E.M.F. AND INTERNAL RESISTANCE","question":"You are provided with an accumulator, an ammeter, a 2 \u03a9 resistor, a key, K, a resistance wire BP, a crocodile clip, J and other necessary materials.  (i) Connect the circuit as shown in the diagram above.  (ii) Use the crocodile clip to hold the resistance wire at D such that BD = d = 80 cm.  (iii) Close the key, read and record the ammeter reading, I. Evaluate I-1  (iv) Repeat the procedure for four other values of d = 70 cm, 50 cm, 40 cm, and 30 cm. In each case, record I and evaluate I-1  (v) Tabulate the results.  (vi) Plot a graph with d on the vertical axis and I-1 on the horizontal axis.  (vii) Determine the slope, s, of the graph.  (viii) State two precautions taken to ensure accurate results.","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,","data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"S/Nd(cm)I(A)I-1(A-1)1800.372.7032700.392.5673500.442.2734400.492.0415300.561.786        (vii) s = \u25b3d\u25b3I\u22121\\frac{\u25b3d}{\u25b3I^{-1}}\u25b3I\u22121\u25b3d\u200b = d2\u2212d1I2\u22121\u2212I1\u22121\\frac{d_{2}-d_{1}}{I^{-1}_{2}-I^{-1}_{1}}I2\u22121\u200b\u2212I1\u22121\u200bd2\u200b\u2212d1\u200b\u200b = 72.5\u221232.52.625\u22121.875\\frac{72.5-32.5}{2.625-1.875}2.625\u22121.87572.5\u221232.5\u200b = 400.75\\frac{40}{0.75}0.7540\u200b = 53.33 cmA    (viii) Precautions:    1. I ensured all electrical connections were tight and secure.    2. I removed the key after each reading to prevent the accumulator from draining unnecessarily.    3. I avoided parallax errors when reading the ammeter to ensure accurate measurements.    4. I ensured the crocodile clip was firmly attached to the resistance wire at the marked points to maintain consistent contact.    5. I avoided kinks or bends in the resistance wire to ensure uniform resistance along its length.    6. I cleaned the terminals of the ammeter and accumulator before starting the experiment to reduce contact resistance.    7. I repeated readings to check for consistency and improve reliability.","marks":"21","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2021>3>b>i","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2021","type":"Practical","sub_label":"i","group":"","topic":"ELECTROMAGNETIC FIELD : MOTOR-GENERATOR EFFECT","question":"State two factors on which the sensitivity of a moving-coil galvanometer depends.","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"The sensitivity of a moving-coil galvanometer depends on several factors, including:    1. Strength of the Magnetic Field: A stronger magnetic field increases the torque on the coil for a given current, improving sensitivity.    2. Number of Turns in the Coil: A larger number of turns in the coil amplifies the torque produced by the current, enhancing sensitivity.    3. Area of the Coil: A larger coil area increases the interaction with the magnetic field, leading to greater sensitivity.    4. Torsional Constant of the Spring: A smaller torsional constant (weaker spring) allows for larger deflections for a given current, making the instrument more sensitive.    5. Damping Mechanism: Proper damping ensures that the pointer settles quickly without overshooting, improving the instrument's responsiveness.    6. Material of the Coil: Using lightweight and highly conductive materials reduces resistance and allows for finer movement, improving sensitivity.    7. Quality of Bearings or Suspension: Frictionless or low-friction pivots or suspension wires ensure minimal energy loss and smooth deflection, contributing to higher sensitivity.","marks":"2","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2021>3>b>ii","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2021","type":"Practical","sub_label":"ii","group":"FINAL","topic":"ELECTRIC FIELD : RESISTIVITY AND CONDUCTIVITY","question":"A resistance wire of diameter 0.6 cm has a resistivity of 1.0 \u00d7 10-6 \u03a9m. What length of the wire would be needed to make a 4 \u03a9 resistor?    (Provide your answer in S.I unit and to 1 d.p e.g 123.123 kg)","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"r = d2\\frac{d}{2}2d\u200b = 0.62\\frac{0.6}{2}20.6\u200b = 0.3 cm = 0.3100\\frac{0.3}{100}1000.3\u200b m    R = \u03c1lA\\frac{\u03c1l}{A}A\u03c1l\u200b    l = RA\u03c1\\frac{RA}{\u03c1}\u03c1RA\u200b = 4\u00d7\u03c0\u00d7(0.3100)21\u00d710\u22126\\frac{4\u00d7\u03c0\u00d7\\left(\\frac{0.3}{100}\\right)^{2}}{1\u00d710^{-6}}1\u00d710\u221264\u00d7\u03c0\u00d7(1000.3\u200b)2\u200b = 36\u03c0 = 113.1 m","marks":"2","difficulty":"1"}];